external.description: Managing AI systems presents a significant challenge for enterprises due to potential agentic sprawl. Microsoft has introduced Agent 365, a control plane for AI agents designed to provide unified observability. This platform offers telemetry, dashboards, and alerts to monitor all active agents, regardless of their origin. Agent 365 supports agents built on Microsoft platforms as well as those from third-party vendors. It aims to transition agents from isolated experiments to enterprise-ready, governed systems. The platform includes five key capabilities: registry, access control, visualization, interoperability, and security. The Entra registry serves as a single source of truth for tracking all agents within an organization. Unique agent IDs and policy enforcement enable granular access control and the blocking of misbehaving agents. Visual dashboards provide insights into agent connections, performance, and adherence to tasks. Agent 365 consolidates various observability tools into a single, governed control plane, offering unified oversight. This approach addresses the growing complexity of managing numerous AI agents. Microsoft advocates managing agents similarly to how people are managed, leveraging existing business infrastructure and protections.
external.title: Microsoft’s Agent 365 shifts AI agents from sandbox tools to enterprise-grade infrastructure

external.description:
Imagine the scene: The frantic efforts of CPR have stopped. The doctor looks at the clock, calls the time of death, and walks away. The family begins to grieve. But then... a pulse returns.

This isn't a scene from a movie. This is the "Lazarus Phenomenon," one of the most baffling and terrifying events in modern medicine. In this episode, we investigate the real-life cases of autoresuscitation, where patients who have been officially declared dead spontaneously return to life. We'll explore a review of dozens of these cases to uncover a shocking truth: this phenomenon, while rare, is likely happening far more often than we know, shrouded in secrecy due to medicolegal concerns and professional fear.

What causes a person to come back from the brink after doctors have given up? We'll break down the science behind Delayed Return of Spontaneous Circulation (ROSC), exploring the leading theories—from delayed drug effects to the hidden impact of CPR itself. This is the ultimate medical mystery that challenges the very definition of death.

More importantly, we'll reveal why doctors are now being urged to change their procedures, extending the observation period from five minutes to ten or more before making the final call. This is a crucial conversation about the ethical and legal lines between life and death, and what we can do to ensure that when someone is declared dead, they truly are.

external.description:
Lately, I've been reminded of the heady days of my agile (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agile_software_development) youth by how often I've found myself asking, "how will we test this?"

As I've mentioned frequently on podcasts and recent Q&As about AI, an odd paradox has emerged in the software industry:

1. Developers experienced in agile engineering practices like test-driven development tend to be among the most skeptical of AI code generation, often citing fears that software quality is being thrown out the window
2. Developers experienced in agile engineering practices like test-driven development tend to be among the most successful at building great software with coding agents, often citing creative techniques enabling agents to verify the correctness of their work

In the late 2000s, I always knew I was talking to a solid programmer if their first question upon being handed a complex task was to ask, "how will we test this?" Agile developers learned back then that literally everything hinged on establishing a fast, reliable, automated way to verify your code fulfilled its intended purpose. Without tests, you can't refactor aggressively, deploy frequently, or delete safely. Over the 2010s, many of us learned patterns and heuristics that allowed us to take shortcuts and tone down our testing zeal in the name of pragmatism and efficiency, but the underlying skill of concocting ways to verify our code never stopped being valuable.

Well, here we are again. In 2025, the only thing that matters when it comes to coding agents like Claude Code and Codex CLI is to ensure they are equipped with the tools they need to independently verify the correctness of their work.
external.title: TDD is more important than ever
